			<div class="content" id="post-content-1055675">
									

<blockquote>
<p>If you need to refer to the Foundation in a document call it the Foundation rather than the SCP. The SCP is what we do, the Foundation is what we are.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Damn good point. Author, go fix that immediately.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: line-through;">I dunno that I agree about sloppiness. And I'm not finding a smiley…</span></p>
<p>Woop, found it. and a lot of other things. Here, I'll point out the worst of it.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The stakes are to have signs emplaced on them to not enter this area without Class D SCP authorization</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Author, go read <a href="http://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/security-clearance-levels">this page</a>. Class D authorization is not a thing.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Controversy over the expungement of Euclid-class SCP specimens has always been a topic of discussion with SCP personnel ever since the SCP's foundation, SCP-793 being one such example. The general consensus about Euclid-class expungement appears to regard SCP-793 as "Not to be demolished", and we agree, albeit there has been still some controversy over the topic.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I'm honestly not sure what you're trying to say here. "expungement" around here is a word meaning "censorship of documents". I think you might be looking for a word meaning "destruction", and even then it's a weird distracted ramble you might as well just cut since it doesn't have anything to do with the SCP object in question.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>B) The hospital's architectural structure appears to be continually sturdy and shows no signs of serious decay, suggesting structural invulnerability. We don't think this should be tested, though! ;)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Please remember that you're writing a reference document for a group of professionals. Jokey tone doesn't fit, and I'm pretty certain someone in character just got fired for that winky face.</p>
<p>Fix those and you'll be pretty okay, though.</p>

